I think we can break this down a bit. We had divided things into:

* stable
* strict

But *actually* strict mode is kind of incomplete (and not very well named). All of this boils down to "ways to prove that impls are disjoint". Really there are three ways:

* "unification failure" -- cannot unify the headers for any value of the impl parameters;
* "negative impl" -- there is a negative impl that proves they are disjoint;
* "implicit negative" -- the old school way, where there is no positive impl and the type is local (or fundamental).

`stable_disjoint` is really "unification failure" OR "implicit negative", and `strict_disjoint` is 'negative impl".

The error messages seem to be expecting and relying "unification failure".

